## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement via `Thread.Abort` — all three APIs (`Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`) throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` or are obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`) in .NET 6+.

### Why it breaks

In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` always throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. There is no way to forcibly terminate a managed thread. You **must** switch to cooperative cancellation.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must check the CancellationToken to respond to cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async overload — preferred in modern .NET.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Caller migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ComputeExpensiveResult(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work must accept and check the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    token =>
    {
        // Check token at regular intervals in long-running work
        for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
        {
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            // ... do a chunk of work ...
        }
        return finalResult;
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---------|------------|
| **Work ignores the token** | Cancellation is *cooperative* — if `work` never checks `token`, it runs to completion regardless of timeout. Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at loop checkpoints. |
| **Blocking calls inside work** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Receive`, etc. won't respond to the token. Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. Use async I/O overloads that accept `CancellationToken`. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer and callback leaks. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Expecting instant termination** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. Design checkpoint frequency around acceptable latency. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If you call a library that can't accept a token, move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` — this is the only safe "force kill" in modern .NET. |

### What was removed and why

| .NET Framework API | Status in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|----|----|----|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` / timeout via constructor |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown | `OperationCanceledException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` to decide whether to continue |
